In this article, President Trump discusses various topics during a press conference on the South Lawn. He mentions the strong state of the economy and predicts success in the upcoming November elections. He also expresses his support for companies reporting their earnings twice a year instead of quarterly. The President defends his decision to revoke the security clearance of former CIA director John Brennan, stating that it gives Brennan a bigger voice and that security clearances are important to him. When asked about critics accusing him of silencing dissent, Trump denies the claim and says he enjoys taking on voices like Brennan's. He also criticizes the ongoing investigation led by Special Counsel Robert Mueller, calling it a "rigged witch hunt" and suggesting that the investigation should focus on the other side. Trump mentions potentially revoking the security clearance of Bruce Ohr, a Justice Department official, and expresses dissatisfaction with Turkey's treatment of an American pastor who is currently on trial. Lastly, the President refuses to comment on the possibility of pardoning Paul Manafort, calling the Manafort trial a "sad day for our country" and defending Manafort's character.